<sup>5</sup>International Confederation of Midwives, The Netherlands</p><sec id="FPar1"><title>Funding</title><p id="Par64">This study is funded by the Laerdal Foundation (Number 40070) through a grant to the International Federation of Gynaecology and Obstetrics (FIGO). The application was peer-reviewed. FIGO acts as a sponsor. The funder had no role in the study design, data collection and management, or the analysis plan.</p></sec><sec id="FPar2"><title>Availability of data and materials</title><p id="Par65">Training materials for the data collectors and the HMS BAB training are available on request. After finalisation of the study we aim to make the data available for wider use.</p></sec></ack><notes notes-type="author-contribution"><title>Authors&#x02019; contributions</title><p>CH and FA conceptualised the study in Tanzania with support from AP, SL and JM. In Uganda, SA, CH and FK conceptualised the study with support from, AJL and JM. GM and CH conceptualised the statistical analysis. CH, AP, FA, SA, SL, JM, FK, GM, HK, AJL, SK, AD, and NM are involved in the operationalisation of the study and data collection support. CH and GM wrote the first draft of this protocol. CH, FA, AP, SA, SL, JM, FK and GM contributed to the protocol development and commented on several drafts of the manuscript. All authors read and approved the final manuscript.</p></notes><notes notes-type="COI-statement"><title>Ethics approval and consent to participate</title><p>We received ethical clearance in Tanzania from the Institutional Review board of Muhimbili University of Health and Allied Sciences (Ref. Nos. 2014-10-06/AEC/Vol.IX/14 and 2015-11-18/AEC/Vol.X/71) and the Commission of Science and Technology (CEST/RCA 2014/254). In Uganda ethical clearance was obtained from the Makerere University School of Medicine Research (Rec 2016-019) and Ethics Committee and the Uganda National Council for Science and Technology (HS2008).</p><p>District Medical Officers in Tanzania and Uganda, Regional Medical Officers (only Tanzania) and all in-charges of health facilities were informed about the study during an inception workshop and with the help of information sheets. Informed consent was received from participating district Medical Officers from each district and the in-charges from the participating health facilities. The study uses abstraction of data documented in the national health management information systems and patient case notes. Due to this, the ethical review committees confirmed that no individual consent was needed from mothers or families. Data were anonymised before uploading them.</p><sec id="FPar4"><title>Consent for publication</title><p id="Par67">Not applicable as no data were published.</p></sec><sec id="FPar5"><title>Competing interests</title><p id="Par68">The authors declare that they have no competing interests.</p></sec><sec id="FPar3"><title>Publisher&#x02019;s Note</title><p id="Par66">Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations.</p></sec></notes><ref-list id="Bib1"><title>References</title><ref id="CR1"><label>1.</label><mixed-citation publication-type="other">United Nations. Sustainable Development Goals. 2015. [cited 2016 May]; <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/sdgs">https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/sdgs</ext-link>. Accessed May 2016.</mixed-citation></ref><ref id="CR2"><label>2.</label><element-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author"><name><surname>Alkema</surname><given-names>L</given-names></name><etal/></person-group><article-title>Global, regional, and national levels and trends in maternal mortality between 1990 and 2015, with scenario-based projections to 2030: a systematic analysis by the UN Maternal Mortality Estimation Inter-Agency Group</article-title><source>Lancet.</source><year>2015</year><volume>387</volume><fpage>462</fpage><lpage>74</lpage><pub